## Notes on the implementation decisions (all live-testable via `app.request()`, no server bound)

- **`zValidator` custom hook**: I did not rely on the library's default failure hook. I passed an explicit third-argument hook to `zValidator('json', itemBody, (result, c) => {...})` so the 400 body is deterministically `{ success: false, error: { name: "ZodError", message: "..." } }`. `Error`/`ZodError` instances don't reliably survive `c.json()`'s `JSON.stringify` with their `name`/`message` as own enumerable keys, so pulling them out explicitly is what makes the shape stable rather than incidental.
- **Middleware order**: `bearerGuard` is listed before `jsonValidator` on both `POST` and `PUT` — this is what makes `POST /items without Bearer → 401` fire even when no `Content-Type`/body is sent at all (validator never runs, so there's nothing to fail-parse first).
- **The RED→GREEN fix** is `app.delete('/items/:id', bearerGuard, (c) => {...})` — in the buggy version this middleware argument was simply omitted, so `DELETE` returned `204` unconditionally regardless of `Authorization`.
- **`app` is built once** at module scope, not per-test; only the module-level `items`/`nextId` state is reset in `beforeEach`. This is safe because each route handler closes over the *binding* `items`, not a snapshotted array reference, so reassignment in `resetStore()` is visible to already-registered handlers.
- **204 has no body**: the DELETE test asserts `await deleteRes.text() === ''` rather than attempting `.json()`, since `new Response(null, { status: 204 })` has no content to parse.
- **CORS is intentionally narrow**: only requests carrying `Origin: https://example.com` get `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` back; there is no wildcard/reflection, matching Hono's documented `cors()` behavior for a string `origin` config.

Everything above exercises real `Web API Response` objects returned by Hono's in-process `app.request()` seam — no mocked `fetch`, no bound port, no network egress beyond the one-time `npm install`.

