## `surprises.md`

```
1. "Delete only on success" is a real architectural choice, not a shortcut: leaving the
   errored message in pgmq means it becomes visible again after vt (30s) and pg_cron (5s
   tick) will pick it up and re-fail it forever unless something moves it to an archive
   or dead-letter queue. For a production variant, pair this with `pgmq.archive()` after
   N read_ct attempts, or check `msg.read_ct` in the EXCEPTION branch and archive instead
   of leaving it live.

2. pg_cron sub-minute schedules ('5 seconds') require pg_cron >= 1.4's "seconds" syntax
   support — confirmed present at 1.6.4 here. Don't assume a hosted/managed pg_cron on an
   older image supports this; it silently rejects finer-than-1-minute cron strings on
   older builds instead of degrading gracefully.

3. pgmq.read's `vt` (visibility timeout) is a *lease*, not a delete-on-read. If your
   worker's transaction is slower than `vt`, another concurrent worker run can re-read
   the same message before you delete it — because two cron ticks 5s apart with vt=30s
   never overlap here, but this is a real double-processing hazard at higher concurrency
   or shorter vt. Size vt conservatively relative to worst-case batch processing time.

4. Function `pgmq.create` is idempotent-ish across versions but not guaranteed identical
   in error behavior everywhere — wrap it defensively (see pipeline.js) rather than
   assuming "already exists" is always silent.

5. Edge Function variant (not used here, noted for future L5/degree work): instead of a
   plpgsql `au_d07_cap_process()` polled by pg_cron, you can have pg_cron/pg_net POST to
   a Supabase Edge Function that does the pgmq.read/delete loop in Deno and calls out to
   an external model/service per message — the same pattern used for Supabase's
   automatic-embeddings trigger→queue→Edge-Function pipeline. Tradeoff: you get real
   HTTP/model-call capability from the worker, but you lose the single-transaction
   atomicity of the in-database BEGIN/EXCEPTION-per-row isolation this capstone relies on
   for R2 — the Edge Function has to reimplement per-row try/catch + explicit
   pgmq.delete itself, and pg_net calls are fire-and-forget from Postgres's point of
   view (no built-in retry-on-5xx without extra bookkeeping).

6. Cleanup is done from a *second* fresh connection deliberately (see pipeline.js
   teardown usage in both test files) — mirrors a real gotcha: if the primary test
   client's socket has gone stale (e.g. after a long poll loop or a crashed assertion),
   teardown on that same client can hang or error, leaving cron/trigger/queue orphaned
   between test runs.
```

